# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: usd-openusd
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] 3D computer graphics, contrary to what the name suggests, are most often displayed on two-dimensional displays.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Unlike 3D film and similar techniques, the result is two-dimensional, without visual depth.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] More often, 3D graphics are being displayed on 3D displays, like in virtual reality systems.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] 3D graphics stand in contrast to 2D computer graphics which typically use completely different methods and formats for creation and rendering.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] 3D computer graphics rely on many of the same algorithms as 2D computer vector graphics in the wire-frame model and 2D computer raster graphics in the final rendered display.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] In computer graphics software, 2D applications may use 3D techniques to achieve effects such as lighting, and similarly, 3D may use some 2D rendering techniques.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] The objects in 3D computer graphics are often referred to as 3D models.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Unlike the rendered image, a model's data is contained within a graphical data file.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] A 3D model is a mathematical representation of *any* three-dimensional object; a model is not technically a *graphic* until it is displayed.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] A model can be displayed visually as a two-dimensional image through a process called 3D rendering, or it can be used in non-graphical computer simulations and calculations.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] With 3D printing, models are rendered into an actual 3D physical representation of themselves, with some limitations as to how accurately the physical model can match the virtual model.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] William Fetter was credited with coining the term *computer graphics* in 1961 to describe his work at Boeing.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] An early example of interactive 3-D computer graphics was explored in 1963 by the Sketchpad program at Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Lincoln Laboratory.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] One of the first displays of computer animation was *Futureworld* (1976), which included an animation of a human face and a hand that had originally appeared in the 1972 experimental short *A Computer Animated Hand*, created by University of Utah students Edwin Catmull and Fred Parke.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D computer graphics software began appearing for home computers in the late 1970s.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] The earliest known example is *3D Art Graphics*, a set of 3-D computer graphics effects, written by Kazumasa Mitazawa and released in June 1978 for the Apple II.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Virtual Reality 3D is a version of 3D computer graphics.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Although the first VR headsets appeared in the late 1950s, VR did not become widely popular until the 2000s.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] In 2012 the Oculus was released and since then, the 3D VR headset world has expanded.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] The modeling describes the process of forming the shape of an object.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] The two most common sources of 3D models are those that an artist or engineer originates on a computer with a 3D modeling tool, or models scanned into a computer from real-world objects (polygonal modeling, patch modeling, and NURBS modeling are some popular tools used in 3D modeling).
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Models can also be produced procedurally or via physical simulation.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Basically, a 3D model is formed from points called vertices that define the shape and form polygons.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] A polygon is an area formed from at least three vertices (a triangle).
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] The overall integrity of the model and its suitability to use in animation depend on the structure of the polygons.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Before rendering into an image, objects must be laid out in a 3D scene.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] This defines spatial relationships between objects, including location and size.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Animation refers to the temporal description of an object (i.e., how it moves and deforms over time).
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Popular methods include keyframing, inverse kinematics, and motion-capture).
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] These techniques are often used in combination.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] As with animation, physical simulation also specifies motion.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Stop Motion has multiple categories within such as Claymation, Cutout, Silhouette, Lego, Puppets, and Pixelation.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Claymation is the use of models made of clay used for an animation.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Some examples are Clay Fighter and Clay Jam.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Lego animation is one of the more common types of stop motion.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Lego stop motion is the use of the figures themselves moving around.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Some examples of this are Lego Island and Lego Harry Potter.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Rendering converts a model into an image either by simulating light transport to get photo-realistic images, or by applying an art style as in non-photorealistic rendering.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] The two basic operations in realistic rendering are transport (how much light gets from one place to another) and scattering (how surfaces interact with light).
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] This step is usually performed using 3-D computer graphics software or a 3-D graphics API.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Altering the scene into a suitable form for rendering also involves 3D projection, which displays a three-dimensional image in two dimensions.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Materials and textures are properties that the render engine uses to render the model.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] One can give the model materials to tell the render engine how to treat light when it hits the surface.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Textures are used to give the material color using a color or albedo map, or give the surface features using a bump map or normal map.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] It can also be used to deform the model itself using a displacement map.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D computer graphics software produces computer-generated imagery (CGI) through 3D modeling and 3D rendering or produces 3-D models for analytical, scientific, entertainment, and industrial purposes.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] There are many varieties of files supporting 3-D graphics, for example, Blender (.blend), Wavefront (.obj), .fbx and .x DirectX files.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Each file type generally tends to have its own unique data structure.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Each file format can be accessed through its respective applications, such as DirectX files, and Quake.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Alternatively, files can be accessed through third-party standalone programs, or via manual decompilation.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modeling software is a class of 3-D computer graphics software used to produce 3-D models.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Individual programs of this class are called modeling applications or modelers.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modeling starts by describing 3 display models: drawing points, drawing lines and drawing triangles and other polygonal patches.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modelers allow users to create and alter models via their 3-D mesh.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Users can add, subtract, stretch and otherwise change the mesh to their desire.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Models can be viewed from a variety of angles, usually simultaneously.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Models can be rotated and the view can be zoomed in and out.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] 3-D modelers can export their models to files, which can then be imported into other applications as long as the metadata are compatible.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Many modelers allow importers and exporters to be plugged-in, so they can read and write data in the native formats of other applications.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Most 3-D modelers contain a number of related features, such as ray tracers and other rendering alternatives and texture mapping facilities.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Some also contain features that support or allow animation of models.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Some may be able to generate full-motion video of a series of rendered scenes (i.e. animation).
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Computer-aided design software may employ the same fundamental 3-D modeling techniques that 3-D modeling software uses but their goal differs.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] They are used in computer-aided engineering, computer-aided manufacturing, Finite element analysis, product lifecycle management, 3D printing and computer-aided architectural design.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] After producing a video, studios then edit or composite the video using programs such as Adobe Premiere Pro or Final Cut Pro at the mid-level, or Autodesk Combustion, Digital Fusion, Shake at the high-end.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Match moving software is commonly used to match live video with computer-generated video, keeping the two in sync as the camera moves.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Use of real-time computer graphics engines to create a cinematic production is called machinima.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Not all computer graphics that appear 3D are based on a wireframe model.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics with 3D photorealistic effects are often achieved without wire-frame modeling and are sometimes indistinguishable in the final form.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Some graphic art software includes filters that can be applied to 2D vector graphics or 2D raster graphics on transparent layers.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Visual artists may also copy or visualize 3D effects and manually render photo-realistic effects without the use of filters.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Some video games use 2.5D graphics, involving restricted projections of three-dimensional environments, such as isometric graphics or virtual cameras with fixed angles, either as a way to improve performance of the game engine or for stylistic and gameplay concerns.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] By contrast, games using 3D computer graphics without such restrictions are said to use true 3D.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Cutout is the use of flat materials such as paper.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Everything is cut out of paper including the environment, characters, and even some props.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Silhouette is similar to cutouts except they are one solid color, black.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Puppets are dolls and different puppets used in the game.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] An example of this would be Yoshi's Wooly World.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] Pixelation is when the entire game appears pixelated, this includes the characters and the environment around them.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-computer-graphics] One example of this is seen in Shovel Knight.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] In 3D computer graphics, **3D modeling** is the process of developing a mathematical coordinate-based representation of a surface of an object (inanimate or living) in three dimensions via specialized software by manipulating edges, vertices, and polygons in a simulated 3D space.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Three-dimensional (3D) models represent a physical body using a collection of points in 3D space, connected by various geometric entities such as triangles, lines, curved surfaces, etc.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Being a collection of data (points and other information), 3D models can be created manually, algorithmically (procedural modeling), or by scanning.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Their surfaces may be further defined with texture mapping.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] The product is called a 3D model, while someone who works with 3D models may be referred to as a 3D artist or a 3D modeler.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] A 3D model can also be displayed as a two-dimensional image through a process called 3D rendering or used in a computer simulation of physical phenomena.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] 3D models may be created automatically or manually.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] The manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] The 3D model can be physically created using 3D printing devices that form 2D layers of the model with three-dimensional material, one layer at a time.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Without a 3D model, a 3D print is not possible.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] 3D modeling software is a class of 3D computer graphics software used to produce 3D models.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Individual programs of this class are called modeling applications.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] 3D models are now widely used anywhere in 3D graphics and CAD but their history predates the widespread use of 3D graphics on personal computers.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] In the past, many computer games used pre-rendered images of 3D models as sprites before computers could render them in real-time.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] The designer can then see the model in various directions and views, this can help the designer see if the object is created as intended to compared to their original vision.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Seeing the design this way can help the designer or company figure out changes or improvements needed to the product.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Simple wireframes were the first versions of early 3D models, which were mainly used to view construction plans and mechanical parts.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Better graphics hardware and software allowed for the creation of solid and surface models in the 1970s and 1980s, giving designers a more realistic and clear representation of physical objects.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] By the 1990s, parametric modeling became popular, letting designers change a model by changing its basic parameters instead of redrawing it from scratch.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Thanks to virtual reality, artificial intelligence and generative design tools, 3D modeling today goes past engineering and is influencing fields like animation, gaming, product design and cinema.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Solid and shell modeling can create functionally identical objects.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Differences between them are mostly variations in the way they are created and edited and conventions of use in various fields and differences in types of approximations between the model and reality.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Shell models must be manifold (having no holes or cracks in the shell) to be meaningful as a real object.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] For example, in a shell model of a cube, all six sides must be connected with no gaps in the edges or the corners.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Polygonal meshes (and to a lesser extent, subdivision surfaces) are by far the most common representation.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Level sets are a useful representation for deforming surfaces that undergo many topological changes, such as fluids.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] The process of transforming representations of objects, such as the middle point coordinate of a sphere and a point on its circumference, into a polygon representation of a sphere is called tessellation.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] This step is used in polygon-based rendering, where objects are broken down from abstract representations ("primitives") such as spheres, cones etc., to so-called *meshes*, which are nets of interconnected triangles.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Meshes of triangles (instead of e.g., squares) are popular as they have proven to be easy to rasterize (the surface described by each triangle is planar, so the projection is always convex).
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Polygon representations are not used in all rendering techniques, and in these cases the tessellation step is not included in the transition from abstract representation to rendered scene.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] The modeling stage consists of shaping individual objects that are later used in the scene.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] In some cases, there is no strict distinction between these phases; in such cases, modeling is just part of the scene creation process (this is the case, for example, with Caligari trueSpace and Realsoft 3D).
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] 3D models can also be created using the technique of Photogrammetry with dedicated programs such as RealityCapture, Metashape and 3DF Zephyr.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Cleanup and further processing can be performed with applications such as MeshLab, the GigaMesh Software Framework, netfabb or MeshMixer.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Photogrammetry creates models using algorithms to interpret the shape and texture of real-world objects and environments based on photographs taken from many angles of the subject.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Complex materials such as blowing sand, clouds, and liquid sprays are modeled with particle systems, and are a mass of 3D coordinates which have either points, polygons, texture splats or sprites assigned to them.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] There are a variety of 3D modeling programs that can be used in the industries of engineering, interior design, film and others.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Each 3D modeling software has specific capabilities and can be utilized to fulfill demands for the industry.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Many programs include export options to form a g-code, applicable to additive or subtractive manufacturing machinery.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] G-code (computer numerical control) works with automated technology to form a real-world rendition of 3D models.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] This code is a specific set of instructions to carry out steps of a product's manufacturing.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] The first widely available commercial application of human virtual models appeared in 1998 on the Lands' End web site.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] The human virtual models were created by the company My Virtual Mode Inc. and enabled users to create a model of themselves and try on 3D clothing.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] There are several modern programs that allow for the creation of virtual human models (Poser being one example).
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] The development of cloth simulation software such as Marvelous Designer, CLO3D and Optitex, has enabled artists and fashion designers to model dynamic 3D clothing on the computer.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Dynamic 3D clothing is used for virtual fashion catalogs, as well as for dressing 3D characters for video games, 3D animation movies, for digital doubles in movies, as a creation tool for digital fashion brands, as well as for making clothes for avatars in virtual worlds such as SecondLife.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] 3D photorealistic effects are often achieved without wire-frame modeling and are sometimes indistinguishable in the final form.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Disadvantages compared to 2D photorealistic rendering may include a software learning curve and difficulty achieving certain photorealistic effects.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Some photorealistic effects may be achieved with special rendering filters included in the 3D modeling software.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] For the best of both worlds, some artists use a combination of 3D modeling followed by editing the 2D computer-rendered images from the 3D model.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] A large market for 3D models (as well as 3D-related content, such as textures, scripts, etc.) exists—either for individual models or large collections.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Several online marketplaces for 3D content allow individual artists to sell content that they have created, including TurboSquid, MyMiniFactory,Patreon,Sketchfab, CGTrader, and Cults.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Often, the artists' goal is to get additional value out of assets they have previously created for projects.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] By doing so, artists can earn more money out of their old content, and companies can save money by buying pre-made models instead of paying an employee to create one from scratch.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] These marketplaces typically split the sale between themselves and the artist that created the asset, artists get 40% to 95% of the sales according to the marketplace.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] In most cases, the artist retains ownership of the 3D model while the customer only buys the right to use and present the model.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Some artists sell their products directly in their own stores, offering their products at a lower price by not using intermediaries.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] The architecture, engineering and construction (AEC) industry is the biggest market for 3D modeling, with an estimated value of $12.13 billion by 2028.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] This is due to the increasing adoption of 3D modeling in the AEC industry, which helps to improve design accuracy, reduce errors and omissions and facilitate collaboration among project stakeholders.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Over the last several years numerous marketplaces specializing in 3D rendering and printing models have emerged.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Some of the 3D printing marketplaces are a combination of models sharing sites, with or without a built in e-com capability.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Some of those platforms also offer 3D printing services on demand, software for model rendering and dynamic viewing of items.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] The term 3D printing or three-dimensional printing is a form of additive manufacturing technology where a three-dimensional object is created from successive layers of material.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Objects can be created without the need for complex and expensive molds or assembly of multiple parts.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] 3D printing allows ideas to be prototyped and tested without having to go through a more time-consuming production process.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] 3D models can be purchased from online markets and printed by individuals or companies using commercially available 3D printers, enabling the home-production of objects such as spare parts and even medical equipment.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Open-source tools (for instance Blender, FreeCAD, MeshLab, OpenSCAD) coexist with commercial packages (some examples are: Autodesk Maya/3ds Max/Fusion 360, SolidWorks, CATIA, Cinema 4D, ZBrush, Rhino, Houdini, SketchUp, CLO 3D/Marvelous Designer, Revit, Archicad).
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] The RDF representation of 3D models can be used in reasoning, which enables intelligent 3D applications which, for example, can automatically compare two 3D models by volume.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Overall, these examples are an illustration of 3D modelling being a tool of general purpose representational layer that creates a bridge between sensing to analysis, design, communication and fabrication.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Despite 3D modelling being widely adopted in various domains, several constraints shape how the technology is utilized.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Access and cost remain an issue in many regions of the world.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Commercial licences, training, and capable hardware can be difficult to find in select regions.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] It can also be out of reach for students and small studios that cannot afford it.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Open-source ecosystems and school programs can aid in making this less of an issue, but availability and support are uneven which in turn creates an equity gap in who can learn and apply 3D modelling.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Workflow complexity is another limitation.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] To practice 3D modelling effectively it requires knowledge of many different things.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] A 3D modelling specialist needs to understand topology, UV mapping, rigging, simulation and rendering for DCC.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] For CAD/CAM modelling parametric constraints, tolerances and manufacturing constraints must be known by the developer.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Information schema and coordination are both required for BIM.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Moving assets between tools can introduce incompatibility issues (meshes vs.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] NURBS/solids/parametric features; unit scaling; normals; material definitions), and format conversions may cause data loss without careful management.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] At scale, energy consumption can be large (this is due to high resolution simulations and rendering and dense 3D scans), which directs teams to try and optimize design complexity and adopting more efficient pipelines.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] In research and heritage work, there is another constraint where ethical and policy questions include provenance, licensing and representation (how “authoritative” a reconstruction should be labelled), especially as these reconstruction are utilized for public communication and educational purposes.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Finally, classroom and outreach deployments must take into account pedagogical support: learners need step by step guidance and clear examples and models to follow.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Without this, the tool’s complexity will be more of a barrier that slows students down instead of enabling them to understand and be creative.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] In 3D modeling, simulations are digital processes that copy how things behave in the real world, in a virtual space.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] Without creating actual prototypes, it lets designers and animators test how objects move, interact, or react to forces.
[src:usd-openusd/3d-modeling] By recreating processes such as collisions, fluid movement, fabric draping, or particle motion, simulations help increase design accuracy, enhance visual effects, and save both time and materials.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The studio started in 1974 as part of the Lucasfilm computer division.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] It was known as the **Graphics Group** before its spin-off as a corporation in 1986, with funding from Apple co-founder Steve Jobs, who became its majority shareholder.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The studio's mascot is Luxo Jr., a desk lamp from the studio's 1986 short film of the same name.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Disney announced its acquisition of Pixar in January 2006, and completed it in May 2006.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Pixar is best known for its feature films, technologically powered by its RenderMan software.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] RenderMan began as Pixar's implementation of the industry-standard RenderMan Interface Specification (RISpec) image-rendering API, which came out in 1988; support for RISpec was dropped in 2016.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] RenderMan became fully path-traced and physically based (PBR).
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In addition to producing short films, Pixar has produced 32 feature films, with its first film being *Toy Story* (1995), which is also the first fully computer-animated feature film, and its most recent film was *Toy Story 5* (2026).
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] As of July 2023, its feature films have earned over $17 billion at the worldwide box office with an average gross of $589 million per film.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] *Toy Story 3* (2010), *Finding Dory* (2016), *Incredibles 2* (2018), *Toy Story 4* (2019) and *Inside Out 2* (2024) all grossed over $1 billion and are among the 50 highest-grossing films of all time.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Moreover, 13 of Pixar's films are in the 50 highest-grossing animated films of all time.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] As of August 2025, *Inside Out 2* was the second highest-grossing animated film of all time.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Pixar has earned 23 Academy Awards, 10 Golden Globe Awards, and 11 Grammy Awards, along with numerous other awards and acknowledgments.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] *Toy Story 3* and *Up* were also nominated for the Academy Award for Best Picture.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In February 2009, Pixar executives John Lasseter, Brad Bird, Pete Docter, Andrew Stanton, and Lee Unkrich were presented with the Golden Lion for Lifetime Achievement by the Venice Film Festival.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The physical award was ceremonially handed to Lucasfilm's founder, George Lucas.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Edwin Catmull and Malcolm Blanchard were the first to be hired and were soon joined by Alvy Ray Smith and David DiFrancesco some months later, who were the four original members of the Computer Graphics Lab, located in a converted two-story garage acquired from the former Vanderbilt-Whitney estate.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Schure invested significant funds into the computer graphics lab, approximately $15 million, providing the resources the group needed but contributing to NYIT's financial difficulties.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Eventually, the group realized they needed to work in a real film studio to reach their goal.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Francis Ford Coppola then invited Smith to his house for a three-day media conference, where Coppola and George Lucas shared their visions for the future of digital moviemaking.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] When Lucas approached the group and offered them jobs at his studio, six employees moved to Lucasfilm.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] During the following months, they gradually resigned from CGL, found temporary jobs for about a year to avoid making Schure suspicious, and joined the Graphics Group at Lucasfilm.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The Graphics Group, which was one-third of the Computer Division of Lucasfilm, opened in 1979 with the hiring of Catmull from NYIT, where he was in charge of the Computer Graphics Lab.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] He was then reunited with Smith, who also made the journey from NYIT to Lucasfilm, and was made the director of the Graphics Group.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] At NYIT, the researchers pioneered many of the CG foundation techniques — in particular, the invention of the alpha channel by Catmull and Smith.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Over the next several years, the CGL would produce a few frames of an experimental film called *The Works*.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] After moving to Lucasfilm, the team worked on creating the precursor to RenderMan, called REYES (for "renders everything you ever saw"), and developed several critical technologies for CG — including particle effects and various animation tools.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] John Lasseter was hired to the Lucasfilm team for a week in late 1983 with the title "interface designer"; he animated the short film *The Adventures of André & Wally B.* In the next few years, a designer suggested naming a new digital compositing computer the "Picture Maker".
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Smith suggested that the laser-based device have a catchier name, and came up with "Pixer", which after a meeting was changed to "Pixar".
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] According to Michael Rubin, the author of *Droidmaker: George Lucas and the Digital Revolution*, Smith and three other employees came up with the name during a restaurant visit in 1981, but when interviewing them he got four different versions about the origin of the name.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In 1982, the Pixar team began working on special-effects film sequences with Industrial Light & Magic.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] After years of research, and key milestones such as the Genesis Effect in *Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan* and the Stained Glass Knight in *Young Sherlock Holmes*, the group, which then numbered 40 individuals, was spun out as a corporation in February 1986 by Catmull and Smith.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Among the 38 remaining employees were Malcolm Blanchard, David DiFrancesco, Ralph Guggenheim, and Bill Reeves, who had been part of the team since the days of NYIT.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Tom Duff, also an NYIT member, would later join Pixar after its formation.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] With Lucas's 1983 divorce, which coincided with the sudden dropoff in revenues from *Star Wars* licenses following the release of *Return of the Jedi*, they knew he would most likely sell the whole Graphics Group.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Worried that the employees would be lost to them if that happened, which would prevent the creation of the first computer-animated movie, they concluded that the best way to keep the team together was to turn the group into an independent company.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] But Moore's Law also suggested that sufficient computing power for the first film was still some years away, and they needed to focus on a proper product until then.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Eventually, they decided they should be a hardware company in the meantime, with their Pixar Image Computer as the core product, a system primarily sold to governmental, scientific, and medical markets.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In 1983, Nolan Bushnell founded a new computer-guided animation studio called Kadabrascope as a subsidiary of his Chuck E.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Cheese's Pizza Time Theatres company (PTT), which was founded in 1977.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Only one major project was made out of the new studio, an animated Christmas special for NBC starring Chuck E.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Cheese and other PTT mascots; known as "Chuck E.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Cheese: The Christmas That Almost Wasn't".
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The animation movement would be made using tweening instead of traditional cel animation.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] After the video game crash of 1983, Bushnell started selling some subsidiaries of PTT to keep the business afloat.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Sente Technologies (another division, which was founded to have games distributed in PTT stores) was sold to Bally Games and Kadabrascope was sold to Lucasfilm.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The Kadabrascope assets were combined with the Computer Division of Lucasfilm.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Coincidentally, one of Steve Jobs's first jobs was under Bushnell in 1973 as a technician at his other company Atari, which Bushnell sold to Warner Communications in 1976 to focus on PTT.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] PTT would later go bankrupt in 1984 and be acquired by ShowBiz Pizza Place.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In 1986, the newly independent Pixar was headed by President Edwin Catmull and Executive Vice President Alvy Ray Smith.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Lucas's search for investors led to an offer from Steve Jobs, which Lucas initially found too low.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] He eventually accepted after determining it impossible to find other investors.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] At that point, Smith and Catmull had been declined by 35 venture capitalists and ten large corporations, including a deal with General Motors which fell through three days before signing the contracts.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Jobs, who had been edged out of Apple in 1985, was now founder and CEO of the new computer company NeXT.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] On February 3, 1986, he paid $5 million of his own money to George Lucas for technology rights and invested $5 million cash as capital into the company, joining the board of directors as chairman.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In 1985, while still at Lucasfilm, Pixar made a deal with the Japanese publisher Shogakukan to produce a computer-animated film titled *Monkey*, based on the Monkey King.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The project continued sometime after they became a separate company in 1986, but it became clear that the technology was not sufficiently advanced.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The computers were not powerful enough and the budget would be too high.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] As a result, they focused on the computer hardware business for years until a computer-animated feature became feasible according to Moore's law.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] At the time, Walt Disney Studios made the decision to develop more efficient ways of producing animation.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] They reached out to Graphics Group at Lucasfilm and to Digital Productions.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Because of the Graphics Group's deeper understanding of animation, and Smith's experience with paint programs at NYIT, it convinced Disney they were the right choice.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The company's first feature film to be released using this new animation method was *The Rescuers Down Under* (1990).
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In a bid to drive sales of the system and increase the company's capital, Jobs suggested releasing the product to the mainstream market.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Pixar employee John Lasseter, who had long been working on not-for-profit short demonstration animations, such as *Luxo Jr.* (1986) to show off the device's capabilities, premiered his creations to great fanfare at SIGGRAPH, the computer graphics industry's largest convention.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] However, the Image Computer had inadequate sales which threatened to end the company as financial losses grew.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Jobs increased investment in exchange for an increased stake, reducing the proportion of management and employee ownership until eventually, his total investment of $50 million gave him control of the entire company.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In 1989, Lasseter's growing animation department which was originally composed of just four people (Lasseter, Bill Reeves, Eben Ostby, and Sam Leffler), was turned into a division that produced computer-animated commercials for outside companies.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In April 1990, Pixar sold its hardware division, including all proprietary hardware technology and imaging software, to Vicom Systems, and transferred 18 of Pixar's approximately 100 employees.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In the same year Pixar moved from San Rafael to Richmond, California.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Pixar released some of its software tools on the open market for Macintosh and Windows systems.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] RenderMan is one of the leading 3D packages of the early 1990s, and Typestry is a special-purpose 3D text renderer that competed with RayDream.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] During this period of time, Pixar continued its successful relationship with Walt Disney Feature Animation, a studio whose corporate parent would ultimately become its most important partner.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] As 1991 began, however, the layoff of 30 employees in the company's computer hardware department (including the company's president, Chuck Kolstad), reduced the total number of employees to just 42, approximately its original number.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] On March 6, 1991, Steve Jobs bought the company from its employees and became the full owner.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] He contemplated folding it into NeXT, but the NeXT's co-founders refused.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] A few months later Pixar made a historic $26 million deal with Disney to produce three computer-animated feature films, the first of which was *Toy Story* (1995), the product of the technological limitations that challenged CGI.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] By then the software programmers working on RenderMan and IceMan, and Lasseter's animation department, which made television commercials (and four Luxo Jr. shorts for *Sesame Street* the same year), were all that remained of Pixar.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Despite the income from these projects, the company still continued to lose money, and Steve Jobs, as chairman of the board and now owner, often considered selling it.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] As late as 1994, Jobs contemplated selling Pixar to other companies such as Hallmark Cards, Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen, and Oracle CEO and co-founder Larry Ellison.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] After learning from New York critics that *Toy Story* would probably be a hit, and confirming that Disney would distribute it for the 1995 Christmas season, he decided to give Pixar another chance.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Also for the first time, he took an active leadership role in the company and made himself CEO.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] *Toy Story* grossed nearly $362 million worldwide during its initial release.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] When Pixar held its initial public offering on November 29, 1995, trading as "PIXR" on NASDAQ, it exceeded Netscape's as the biggest IPO of the year.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In its first half-hour of trading, Pixar stock shot from $28 to $45, delaying trading because of unmatched buy orders.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Shares climbed to US$50 and closed the day at $42.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The company continued to make the television commercials during the production of *Toy Story*, which came to an end on July 9, 1996, when Pixar announced they would shut down its television commercial unit, which counted 18 employees, to focus on longer projects and interactive entertainment.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] According to Catmull, it evolved out of the working relationship between Lasseter, Andrew Stanton, Pete Docter, Lee Unkrich, and Joe Ranft on *Toy Story*.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] As a result of the success of *Toy Story*, Pixar built a new studio at the Emeryville campus, which was designed by PWP Landscape Architecture and opened in November 2000.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Pixar and Disney had disagreements over the production of *Toy Story 2*.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Originally intended as a direct-to-video release (and thus not part of Pixar's three-picture deal), the film was eventually upgraded to a theatrical release during production.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Pixar demanded that the film then be counted toward the three-picture agreement, but Disney refused.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Though profitable for both, Pixar later complained that the arrangement was not equitable.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Pixar was responsible for creation and production, while Disney handled marketing and distribution.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Profits and production costs were split equally, but Disney exclusively owned all story, character, and sequel rights and also collected a 10–15% distribution fee.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The two companies attempted to reach a new agreement for ten months and failed on January 26, 2001, July 26, 2002, April 22, 2003, January 16, 2004, July 22, 2004, and January 14, 2005.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The proposed distribution deal meant Pixar would control production and own the resulting story, character, and sequel rights, while Disney would own the right of first refusal to distribute any sequels.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Pixar also wanted to finance its own films and collect 100% profit, paying Disney the 10–15% distribution fee.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In addition, as part of any distribution agreement with Disney, Pixar demanded control over films already in production under the new agreement, including *The Incredibles* (2004) and *Cars* (2006).
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Disney considered these conditions unacceptable, but Pixar would not concede.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Disagreements between Steve Jobs and Disney chairman and CEO Michael Eisner caused the negotiations to cease in 2004, with Disney forming Circle Seven Animation and Jobs declaring that Pixar was actively seeking partners other than Disney.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Despite this announcement and several talks with Warner Bros.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Pictures, Sony Pictures, and 20th Century Fox, Pixar did not enter negotiations with other distributors, although a Warner Bros. spokesperson told CNN, "We would love to be in business with Pixar.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] They are a great company." After a lengthy hiatus, negotiations between the two companies resumed following the departure of Eisner from Disney in September 2005.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In preparation for potential fallout between Pixar and Disney, Jobs announced in late 2004 that Pixar would no longer release movies at the Disney-dictated November time frame, but during the more lucrative early summer months.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] This would also allow Pixar to release DVDs for its major releases during the Christmas shopping season.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] An added benefit of delaying *Cars* from November 4, 2005, to June 9, 2006, was to extend the time frame remaining on the Pixar-Disney contract, to see how things would play out between the two companies.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Pending the Disney acquisition of Pixar, the two companies created a distribution deal for the intended 2007 release of *Ratatouille*, to ensure that if the acquisition failed or closing was delayed, the film would be released through Disney's distribution channels.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In contrast to earlier Disney-Pixar films, *Ratatouille*'s production costs were paid by Pixar, with Disney just responsible for distribution.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] After extended negotiations, Disney ultimately agreed on January 24, 2006, to buy Pixar for approximately $7.4 billion in an all-stock deal.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Following Pixar shareholder approval, the acquisition was completed on May 5, 2006.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The transaction catapulted Jobs, who owned 49.65% of total share interest in Pixar, to Disney's largest individual shareholder with 7%, valued at $3.9 billion, and a new seat on its board of directors.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Jobs' new Disney holdings exceeded holdings belonging to Eisner, the previous top shareholder, who still held 1.7%; and Disney Director Emeritus Roy E.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Disney, who held almost 1% of the corporation's shares.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Pixar shareholders received 2.3 shares of Disney common stock for each share of Pixar common stock redeemed.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] As part of the deal, John Lasseter, by then Executive Vice President, became Chief Creative Officer (reporting directly to president and CEO Bob Iger and consulting with Disney Director Roy E.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Disney) of both Pixar and Walt Disney Animation Studios (including its division Disneytoon Studios), as well as the Principal Creative Adviser at Walt Disney Imagineering, which designs and builds the company's theme parks.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Catmull retained his position as President of Pixar, while also becoming President of Walt Disney Animation Studios, reporting to Iger and Dick Cook, chairman of the Walt Disney Studios.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Jobs's position as Pixar's chairman and chief executive officer was abolished, and instead, he took a place on the Disney board of directors.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] After the deal closed in May 2006, Lasseter revealed that Iger had felt that Disney needed to buy Pixar while watching a parade at the opening of Hong Kong Disneyland in September 2005.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Iger noticed that of all the Disney characters in the parade, none were characters that Disney had created within the last ten years since all the newer ones had been created by Pixar.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Lasseter and Catmull's oversight of both the Disney Feature Animation and Pixar studios did not mean that the two studios were merging, however.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In fact, additional conditions were laid out as part of the deal to ensure that Pixar remained a separate entity, a concern that analysts had expressed about the Disney deal.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Some of those conditions were that Pixar HR policies would remain intact, including the lack of employment contracts.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Also, the Pixar name was guaranteed to continue, and the studio would remain in its current Emeryville, California, location with the "Pixar" sign.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Finally, branding of films made post-merger would be "Disney•Pixar" (beginning with *Cars*).
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Jim Morris, producer of *WALL-E* (2008), became general manager of Pixar.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In this new position, Morris took charge of the day-to-day running of the studio facilities and products.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] After a few years, Lasseter and Catmull were able to successfully transfer the basic principles of the Pixar Braintrust to Disney Animation, although meetings of the Disney Story Trust are reportedly "more polite" than those of the Pixar Braintrust.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The rule ensures that each studio maintains "local ownership" of projects and can be proud of its own work.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Thus for example, when Pixar had issues with *Ratatouille* and Disney Animation had issues with *Bolt* (2008), "nobody bailed them out" and each studio was required "to solve the problem on its own" despite knowing that there were personnel at the other studio who theoretically could have helped.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] On April 20, 2010, Pixar opened Pixar Canada in the downtown area of Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The roughly 2,000-square-meter (22,000 sq ft) studio produced seven short films based on *Toy Story* and *Cars* characters.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In October 2013, the studio was closed down to refocus Pixar's efforts at its main headquarters.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In November 2014, Morris was promoted to president of Pixar, while his counterpart at Disney Animation, general manager Andrew Millstein, was also promoted to president of that studio.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Both continued to report to Catmull, who retained the title of president of both Disney Animation and Pixar.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] On November 21, 2017, Lasseter announced that he was taking a six-month leave of absence after acknowledging what he called "missteps" in his behavior with employees in a memo to staff.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] According to *The Hollywood Reporter* and *The Washington Post*, Lasseter had a history of alleged sexual misconduct towards employees.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] On June 8, 2018, it was announced that Lasseter would leave Disney Animation and Pixar at the end of the year, but would take on a consulting role until then.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Pete Docter was announced as Lasseter's replacement as chief creative officer of Pixar on June 19, 2018.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] On June 15, 2018, *Incredibles 2* was released, setting a record for widest opening weekend worldwide and domestic for an animated film.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The film would eventually gross $1.2 billion worldwide.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] On October 23, 2018, it was announced that Catmull would be retiring.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] He stayed in an adviser role until July 2019.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] On January 18, 2019, it was announced that Lee Unkrich would be leaving Pixar after 25 years although he would return to the studio a few years later.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] On June 21, 2019, *Toy Story 4* was released, surpassing the widest opening worldwide weekend record that *Incredibles 2* set.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The film would make over $1 billion and win the Academy Award for Best Animated Feature.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] During the 2019 D23 Expo, Pixar announced that their next film, *Soul*, would release in 2020.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Ahead of the launch of Disney+, Pixar debuted *SparkShorts*, experimental shorts done by Pixar staff.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Pixar released *Onward* on March 6, 2020.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] However, due to the start of the COVID-19 pandemic, the film underperformed at the box office and was released onto rental digital services on March 20, and later on Disney+ on April 3.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Due to the pandemic, *Soul* was moved to November 2020, and ultimately released on December 25, 2020, on Disney+ at no additional cost to subscribers, and later became the first animated streaming film to win the Academy Award for Best Animated Feature.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Pixar's next two features, *Luca* and *Turning Red*, were also released free on Disney+ in June 2021 and March 2022, respectively.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In 2021, several Pixar employees anonymously criticized Disney's decision to release their films direct to Disney+.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] During that same month, *Elemental* was released.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] During the film's opening weekend, Docter stated that Pixar "trained audiences that these films will be available for you on Disney+".
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Despite opening below projections, *Elemental* ultimately made a box office comeback by early August 2023, crossing $430 million at the worldwide box office.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] And then we have revenue from streaming, theme parks and consumer products.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] This will certainly be a profitable film for the Disney company." In December 2023, it was announced that *Soul*, *Turning Red* and *Luca* would be released in theaters in the United States in the first quarter of 2024.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In January 2024, it was reported that Pixar's staff would face imminent layoffs by 20 percent, reducing the studio's workforce to less than 1,000 employees.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] However, the layoffs were then delayed and did not occur, reportedly because of production schedules.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In May 2024, the studio proceeded with slightly smaller layoffs: 175 employees or approximately 14 percent of the studio's workforce of over 1,300 employees.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The layoffs occurred as the studio began to rely less on direct-to-streaming series and more on feature films intended primarily for theatrical exhibition.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] On June 14 of the same year, *Inside Out 2* was released and became financially successful.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The film had a domestic opening of $165 million, the third highest for an animated film, and the biggest global opening for an animated movie with $319 million.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Since then, *Inside Out 2* broke multiple box office records.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] It had the highest second weekend gross for an animated film with $100 million, being the first to reach the six-digit second opening weekend.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] It became the fastest animated movie to reach $1 billion at the global box office, reaching the milestone in 17 days.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] It also out-grossed *Incredibles 2* to become the highest grossing Pixar film.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] *Inside Out 2* became the highest-grossing animated film, and the 8th-highest-grossing film of all time at the end of its theatrical run.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] *Dream Productions*, an *Inside Out* spin off series set between the first and second film, was released on December 11, 2024, on Disney+.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In June 2025, Pixar released their next film *Elio*.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The film had the lowest box office opening for a Pixar film to date, earning $25 million, and an all-time low global opening of $39 million.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In an op-ed, Rebecca Rubin for *Variety* noted that *Elio* faced stiff box office competition against the 2025 live-action remakes of *How to Train Your Dragon* and Disney's *Lilo & Stitch*.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Shawn Robbins for Fandango observed, "Competition from family audiences was difficult to overcome.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] It makes you wonder how *Elio* would have performed in the spring, or even a week or two later." Rubin wrote that similar to *Elemental*, *Elio* could have steady box office longevity thanks to favorable reviews and positive word-of-mouth.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] However, *Elio* underperformed at the box office, earning $154 million worldwide.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] On September 17, 2025, *Elio* began streaming on Disney+ and became one of the top-streaming titles for that week.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In March 2026, *Hoppers* was released to positive reviews.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] During its opening weekend, it garnered $45.3 million in the United and Canada and $42 million overseas for a worldwide total of $88 million, taking first place at the box office.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] It was also the highest opening for an original Pixar film since *Coco* and the best opening for an original animated film.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The first of several buildings, the high-tech structure designed by Bohlin Cywinski Jackson has special foundations and electricity generators to ensure continued film production, even through major earthquakes.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The character of the building is intended to abstractly recall Emeryville's industrial past.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The two-story steel-and-masonry building is a collaborative space with many pathways.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The digital revolution in filmmaking was driven by applied mathematics, including computational physics and geometry.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In 2008, this led Pixar senior scientist Tony DeRose to offer to host the second Julia Robinson Mathematics Festival at the Emeryville campus.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Some of Pixar's first animators were former cel animators including John Lasseter, and others came from computer animation or were fresh college graduates.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] A large number of animators that make up its animation department had been hired around the releases of *A Bug's Life* (1998), *Monsters, Inc.* (2001), and *Finding Nemo* (2003).
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The success of *Toy Story* (1995) made Pixar the first major computer-animation studio to successfully produce theatrical feature films.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The majority of the animation industry was (and still is) located in Los Angeles, and Pixar is located 350 miles (560 km) north in the San Francisco Bay Area.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Traditional hand-drawn animation was still the dominant medium for feature animated films.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] With the scarcity of Los Angeles-based animators willing to move their families so far north to give up traditional animation and try computer animation, Pixar's new hires at this time either came directly from college or had worked outside feature animation.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] For traditional animators, the Pixar animation software Marionette was designed to require minimal training before becoming productive.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In a 2007 interview with PBS talk show host Tavis Smiley, Lasseter said that Pixar's films follow the same theme of self-improvement as the company itself has: with the help of friends or family, a character ventures out into the real world and learns to appreciate his friends and family.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Actor John Ratzenberger has voiced a character in every Pixar feature film from *Toy Story* through *Onward* (2020).
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In addition, a non-speaking background character in *Soul* (2020) bears his likeness.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Additionally, Pixar is known for their films having expensive budgets, ranging from $150–250 million.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In a 2023 interview, Pixar's president Jim Morris stated that one of the reasons why their films have expensive budgets is because they are produced entirely in the U.S. with all of the artists under one roof, while almost all of their competitors keep costs down by doing work offshore.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] As of March 2025, seven Pixar films have received or will receive sequels or prequels.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] These films are *Toy Story*, *Cars*, *Monsters, Inc.*, *Finding Nemo*, *The Incredibles*, *Inside Out*, and *Coco*.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Following the release of *Toy Story 2* in 1999, Pixar and Disney had a gentlemen's agreement that Disney would not make any sequels without Pixar's involvement though retaining a right to do so.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] After the two companies were unable to agree on a new deal, Disney announced in 2004 they would plan to move forward on sequels with or without Pixar and put *Toy Story 3* into pre-production at Disney's then-new CGI division Circle Seven Animation.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] However, when Lasseter was placed in charge of all Disney and Pixar animation following Disney's acquisition of Pixar in 2006, he put all sequels on hold and *Toy Story 3* was canceled.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In May 2006, it was announced that *Toy Story 3* was back in pre-production with a new plot and under Pixar's control.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The film was released on June 18, 2010, as Pixar's eleventh feature film.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Shortly after announcing the resurrection of *Toy Story 3*, Lasseter stated, "If we have a great story, we'll do a sequel." *Cars 2*, Pixar's first non-*Toy Story* sequel, was officially announced in April 2008 and released on June 24, 2011, as their twelfth.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] *Monsters University*, a prequel to *Monsters, Inc.* (2001), was announced in April 2010 and initially set for release in November 2012; the release date was pushed to June 21, 2013, due to Pixar's past success with summer releases, according to a Disney executive.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In June 2011, Tom Hanks, who voiced Woody in the *Toy Story* series, implied that *Toy Story 4* was "in the works", although it had not yet been confirmed by the studio.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In April 2013, *Finding Dory*, a sequel to *Finding Nemo*, was announced for a June 17, 2016, release.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In March 2014, *Incredibles 2* and *Cars 3* were announced as films in development.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In November 2014, *Toy Story 4* was confirmed to be in development with Lasseter serving as director.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] However, in July 2017, Lasseter announced that he had stepped down, leaving Josh Cooley as sole director.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Released in June 2019, *Toy Story 4* ranks among the 40 top-grossing films in American cinema.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] On July 3, 2016, Pixar president Jim Morris announced that the studio might be moving away from sequels after *Toy Story 4*.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] This was affirmed by producer Mark Nielsen in May 2019.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Shortly after its release, Pixar's chief creative officer Pete Docter confirmed that the studio would take a break from sequels and focus on original projects.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] However, in a later interview, Docter said the studio would have to return to making sequels at some point for its "financial safety".
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In September 2022, during the D23 Expo, Docter and Amy Poehler (voice of Joy in *Inside Out*) confirmed that *Inside Out 2* was in development, with the film being released on June 14, 2024.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In February 2023, Disney CEO Bob Iger announced that *Toy Story 5* was in development, aiming for a 2026 release.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In August 2024, during the D23 Expo, Docter announced that *Incredibles 3* is in development, with Brad Bird returning to develop.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] That same month, on the subject of making a sequel, Docter stated "I want to make it because we have something new to say with these characters.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In March 2025, Iger announced that *Coco 2* is in development.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Lee Unkrich and Adrian Molina are returning as directors respectively while Mark Nielsen is producing.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] As of March 2025, it is tentatively scheduled for release in 2029.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] On December 10, 2020, it was announced that three series would be released on Disney+.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The first *Dug Days* (featuring Dug from *Up* (2009)), which premiered on September 1, 2021.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The second, a *Cars* show titled *Cars on the Road*, which follows Mater and Lightning McQueen as they go on a road trip.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] It premiered on Disney+ on September 8, 2022.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] An original show entitled *Win or Lose*, which follows a middle school softball team the week leading up to the big championship game where each episode is from a different perspective, premiered on Disney+ on February 19, 2025.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] A TV series based on *Inside Out* was announced to be in development for Disney+ in June 2023, with *Soul* co-writer Mike Jones hired as developer.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The series, titled *Dream Productions*, premiered on Disney+ on December 11, 2024.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] On August 8, 2025, it was announced that a series is being developed as the third series in the *Cars* franchise, titled *Cars: Lightning Racers*.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] It is set to be released on Disney Jr. in 2027.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The Pixar filmography to date has been computer-animated features.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] *1906*, the live-action film by Brad Bird based on a screenplay and novel by James Dalessandro about the 1906 earthquake, was in development but has since been abandoned by Bird and Pixar.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Bird has stated that he was "interested in moving into the live-action realm with some projects" while "staying at Pixar [because] it's a very comfortable environment for me to work in".
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In June 2018, Bird mentioned the possibility of adapting the novel as a TV series, and the earthquake sequence as a live-action feature film.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The *Toy Story Toons* short *Hawaiian Vacation* (2011) also includes the fish and shark as live-action.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Jim Morris, president of Pixar, produced Disney's *John Carter* (2012) which Andrew Stanton co-wrote and directed.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Pixar's creative heads were consulted to fine tune the script for the 2011 live-action film *The Muppets*.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Similarly, Pixar assisted in the story development of Disney's *The Jungle Book* (2016) as well as providing suggestions for the film's end credits sequence.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Both Pixar and Mark Andrews were given a "Special Thanks" credit in the film's credits.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Additionally, many Pixar animators, both former and current, were recruited for a traditional hand-drawn animated sequence for the 2018 film *Mary Poppins Returns*.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Pixar representatives have also assisted in the English localization of several Studio Ghibli films, mainly those by Hayao Miyazaki.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] In 2019, Pixar developed a live-action hidden camera reality show, titled *Pixar in Real Life*, for Disney+.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] Indicates films playing in theaters in the week commencing 26 June 2026.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The Pixar Co-op Program, a part of the Pixar University professional development program, allows Pixar employees to use Pixar resources to produce independent films.
[src:usd-openusd/pixar] The first 3D project accepted to the program was *Borrowed Time* (2016); all previously accepted films were live-action.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] In 3D computer graphics and solid modeling, a **polygon mesh** is a collection of **vertices**, **edges** and **faces** that define the shape of a polyhedral object's surface.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] It simplifies rendering, as in a wire-frame model.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] The faces usually consist of triangles (triangle mesh), quadrilaterals (quads), or other simple convex polygons (n-gons).
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] A polygonal mesh may also be more generally composed of concave polygons, or even polygons with holes.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] The study of polygon meshes is a large sub-field of computer graphics (specifically 3D computer graphics) and geometric modeling.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Different representations of polygon meshes are used for different applications and goals.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] The variety of operations performed on meshes includes Boolean logic (Constructive solid geometry), smoothing, and simplification.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Algorithms also exist for ray tracing, collision detection, and rigid-body dynamics with polygon meshes.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] If the mesh's edges are rendered instead of the faces, then the model becomes a wireframe model.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Several methods exist for mesh generation, including the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Volumetric meshes are distinct from polygon meshes in that they explicitly represent both the surface and interior region of a structure, while polygon meshes only explicitly represent the surface (the volume is implicit).
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Objects created with polygon meshes must store different types of elements.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] These include vertices, edges, faces, polygons and surfaces.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] In many applications, only vertices, edges and either faces or polygons are stored.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] A renderer may support only 3-sided faces, so polygons must be constructed of many of these, as shown above.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] However, many renderers either support quads and higher-sided polygons, or are able to convert polygons to triangles on the fly, making it unnecessary to store a mesh in a triangulated form.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] A vertex in computer graphics terms is a data structure that describes the position of a point in 2, 3 or 4D space on a surface along with optional attributes - other values used to render the object correctly.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Most attributes of a vertex represent vectors in the space to be rendered.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] These vectors are typically 2 (*x, y*) or 3 (*x, y, z*) dimensional and can include a fourth homogeneous coordinate (*w*)..
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] In real-time rendering these properties are used by a vertex shader or vertex pipeline.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Attributes can include position, color, reflectance, specularity, texture mapping coordinates, normal vectors, and displacement mapping.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Polygon meshes may be represented in a variety of ways, using different methods to store the vertex, edge and face data.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Each representation has advantages and disadvantages, discussed in Smith (2006).
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of vertices connected to other vertices.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] This is the simplest representation, but not widely used since the face and edge information is implicit.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Thus, it is necessary to traverse the data in order to generate a list of faces for rendering.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] In addition, operations on edges and faces are not easily accomplished.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] However, VV meshes benefit from small storage space and efficient morphing of shape.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows a four-sided box as represented by a VV mesh.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Each vertex indexes its neighboring vertices.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] The last two vertices, 8 and 9 at the top and bottom center of the "box-cylinder", have four connected vertices rather than five.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] A general system must be able to handle an arbitrary number of vertices connected to any given vertex.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] For a complete description of VV meshes see Smith (2006).
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of faces and a set of vertices.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] This is the most widely used mesh representation, being the input typically accepted by modern graphics hardware.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes improve on VV mesh for modelling in that they allow explicit lookup of the vertices of a face, and the faces surrounding a vertex.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" example as an FV mesh.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Vertex v5 is highlighted to show the faces that surround it.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Notice that, in this example, every face is required to have exactly 3 vertices.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] However, this does not mean every vertex has the same number of surrounding faces.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] For rendering, the face list is usually transmitted to the GPU as a set of indices to vertices, and the vertices are sent as position/color/normal structures (in the figure, only position is given).
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] This has the benefit that changes in shape, but not geometry, can be dynamically updated by simply resending the vertex data without updating the face connectivity.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Modelling requires easy traversal of all structures.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] With face-vertex meshes it is easy to find the vertices of a face.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Also, the vertex list contains a list of faces connected to each vertex.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Unlike VV meshes, both faces and vertices are explicit, so locating neighboring faces and vertices is constant time.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] However, the edges are implicit, so a search is still needed to find all the faces surrounding a given face.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Other dynamic operations, such as splitting or merging a face, are also difficult with face-vertex meshes.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Introduced by Baumgart in 1975, winged-edge meshes explicitly represent the vertices, faces, and edges of a mesh.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] This representation is widely used in modelling programs to provide the greatest flexibility in dynamically changing the mesh geometry, because split and merge operations can be done quickly.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Their primary drawback is large storage requirements and increased complexity due to maintaining many indices.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] A good discussion of implementation issues of Winged-edge meshes may be found in the book *Graphics Gems II*.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes address the issue of traversing from edge to edge, and providing an ordered set of faces around an edge.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] For any given edge, the number of outgoing edges may be arbitrary.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] To simplify this, winged-edge meshes provide only four, the nearest clockwise and counter-clockwise edges at each end.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] The other edges may be traversed incrementally.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] The information for each edge therefore resembles a butterfly, hence "winged-edge" meshes.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" as a winged-edge mesh.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] The total data for an edge consists of 2 vertices (endpoints), 2 faces (on each side), and 4 edges (winged-edge).
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Rendering of winged-edge meshes for graphics hardware requires generating a face index list, which is usually done only when the geometry changes.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are ideally suited for dynamic geometry, such as subdivision surfaces and interactive modelling, since changes to the mesh can occur locally.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Traversal across the mesh, as might be needed for collision detection, can be accomplished efficiently.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are not the only representation which allows for dynamic changes to geometry.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] A representation which combines winged-edge meshes and face-vertex meshes is the render dynamic mesh (RDM), which explicitly stores both, the vertices of a face and faces of a vertex (like FV meshes), and the faces and vertices of an edge (like winged-edge).
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] RDM's require less storage space than standard winged-edge meshes, and can be directly rendered by graphics hardware since the face list contains an index of vertices.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] In addition, traversal from vertex to face is explicit (constant time), as is from face to vertex.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] RDM's do not require the four outgoing edges since these can be found by traversing from edge to face, then face to neighboring edge.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] RDM's benefit from the features of winged-edge meshes by allowing for geometry to be dynamically updated.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] See Tobler & Maierhofer (WSCG 2006) for more details.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] The notation *avg(V,V)* means the average number of vertices connected to a given vertex; *avg(E,V)* means the average number of edges connected to a given vertex, and *avg(F,V)* is the average number of faces connected to a given vertex.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] The notation "V → f1, f2, f3, ... → v1, v2, v3, ..." describes that a traversal across multiple elements is required to perform the operation.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] For example, to get "all vertices around a given vertex V" using the face-vertex mesh, it is necessary to first find the faces around the given vertex V using the vertex list.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Then, from those faces, use the face list to find the vertices around them.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes explicitly store nearly all information, and other operations always traverse to the edge first to get additional info.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are the only representation that explicitly stores the neighboring vertices of a given vertex.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] As the mesh representations become more complex (from left to right in the summary), the amount of information explicitly stored increases.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] This gives more direct, constant time, access to traversal and topology of various elements but at the cost of increased overhead and space in maintaining indices properly.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] As a general rule, face-vertex meshes are used whenever an object must be rendered on graphics hardware that does not change geometry (connectivity), but may deform or morph shape (vertex positions) such as real-time rendering of static or morphing objects.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge or render dynamic meshes are used when the geometry changes, such as in interactive modeling packages or for computing subdivision surfaces.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are ideal for efficient, complex changes in geometry or topology so long as hardware rendering is not of concern.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes store faces in an ordered, yet independent, way so that the mesh can be transmitted in pieces.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] The order of faces may be spatial, spectral, or based on other properties of the mesh.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes allow a very large mesh to be rendered even while it is still being loaded.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Progressive meshes transmit the vertex and face data with increasing levels of detail.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Unlike *streaming meshes*, progressive meshes give the overall shape of the entire object, but at a low level of detail.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Additional data, new edges and faces, progressively increase the detail of the mesh.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes transmit progressive changes to a mesh as a set of normal displacements from a base mesh.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] With this technique, a series of textures represent the desired incremental modifications.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes are compact, since only a single scalar value is needed to express displacement.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] However, the technique requires a complex series of transformations to create the displacement textures.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] There exist many different file formats for storing polygon mesh data.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Each format is most effective when used for the purpose intended by its creator.
[src:usd-openusd/polygon-mesh] Popular formats include .fbx, .dae, .obj, and .stl.
[src:usd-openusd/universal-scene-description] It is developed by Pixar and was first published as open source software in 2016, under a modified Apache license.
